##Using multimedia in HTML
1.Images in HTML
Images improve the design and layout of a webpage.
In order to place a simple image on a webpage, use the <img> tag.

Basic <img> tag syntax
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">

#Common Image Attributes
1. src (source)
Specifies the path or URL of the image.

<img src="cat.jpg">

2. alt (alternative text)
Provides text description if the image fails to load or for screen readers.

<img src="cat.jpg" alt="Cute cat">

3. width
Sets the width of the image (in pixels or percentage).

<img src="cat.jpg" width="200">

4. height
Sets the height of the image.

<img src="cat.jpg" height="150">

5. title
Shows a tooltip text when the mouse hovers over the image.

<img src="cat.jpg" alt="Cat" title="This is a cute cat">

6. loading
Controls lazy loading of images.

<img src="cat.jpg" alt="Cat" loading="lazy">

Values:
lazy → loads image when it comes into view
eager → loads immediately

7. srcset
Provides multiple image sizes for responsive design.

<img src="small.jpg" 
     srcset="small.jpg 500w, medium.jpg 1000w, large.jpg 1500w"
     alt="Responsive image">

8. sizes
Works with srcset to define image display size.

<img src="small.jpg"
     srcset="small.jpg 500w, large.jpg 1000w"
     sizes="(max-width: 600px) 500px, 1000px"
     alt="Responsive image">

Example with multiple attributes
<img src="dog.jpg"
     alt="Brown dog"
     width="300"
     height="200"
     title="Friendly dog"
     loading="lazy">


##Audio in html
The <audio> tag specifies a standard way to embed audio in a web page.
Web browsers generally support a variety of audio format each with its own natively built in controls.

HTML Audio (<audio> tag)

The <audio> tag is used to embed sound or music in a web page.

Basic Syntax
<audio src="song.mp3"></audio>


But usually, we add controls so the user can play or pause the audio.

Audio with Controls
<audio src="song.mp3" controls></audio>

This shows:
*Play button
*Pause button
*Volume control
*Timeline

Using <source> for Multiple Formats

Different browsers support different audio formats.
So we use <source> inside <audio>.

<audio controls>
    <source src="song.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
    <source src="song.ogg" type="audio/ogg">
    Your browser does not support the audio element.
</audio>

Common <audio> Attributes
Attribute		Description
controls		Shows play/pause buttons
autoplay		Starts audio automatically
loop			Repeats audio continuously
muted			Starts audio with no sound
preload			Controls how audio loads

Example with Attributes
<audio controls autoplay loop muted>
    <source src="music.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
</audio>


HTML Video (<video> tag)

The <video> tag is used to embed videos in a web page, just like the <audio> tag is used for sound.

Basic Syntax
<video src="video.mp4"></video>

Usually, we add controls so the user can play, pause, and control the video.

Video with Controls
<video src="video.mp4" controls></video>

This shows:
*Play/Pause button
*Volume control
*Timeline
*Fullscreen option

Using <source> for Multiple Formats
Different browsers support different video formats.
So we use multiple <source> elements.

<video controls>
    <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
    <source src="video.webm" type="video/webm">
    Your browser does not support the video tag.
</video>

#Common <video> Attributes
Attribute		Description
controls		Shows video controls
autoplay		Plays video automatically
loop			Repeats the video
muted			Starts video without sound
poster			Shows an image before video plays
width			Sets video width
height			Sets video height
preload			Controls how video loads

Example with Attributes
<video width="400" controls poster="thumbnail.jpg">
    <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>